## 10. Main API Endpoints

### Create User

```txt
POST /user
```

Example request body:

```json
{
  "email": "user1@example.com",
  "username": "user1",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123"
}
```

Expected result:

```txt
201 Created
```

The response should return only safe user information and must not expose the password or password hash.

---

### Login

```txt
POST /auth/login
```

Example request body:

```json
{
  "email": "user1@example.com",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123"
}
```

Expected response:

```json
{
  "message": "Login successful",
  "user": {
    "id": "uuid-here",
    "email": "user1@example.com",
    "username": "user1",
    "role": "user"
  }
}
```

After successful login, the backend creates a JWT and stores it in a signed HttpOnly cookie.

---

### Get Current Authenticated User

```txt
GET /auth/me
```

This endpoint returns the currently logged-in user based on the authentication cookie.

Expected response after login:

```json
{
  "id": "uuid-here",
  "email": "user1@example.com",
  "username": "user1",
  "role": "user"
}
```

Expected response without login:

```txt
401 Unauthorized
```

---

### Get All Users

```txt
GET /users
```

This is a protected route. The request must include a valid authentication cookie.

Expected response without login:

```txt
401 Unauthorized
```

Expected response after login:

```json
[
  {
    "id": "uuid-here",
    "email": "user1@example.com",
    "username": "user1",
    "role": "user"
  }
]
```

Security note: this endpoint returns all users. In a production system, this should normally be restricted to admin users only.

---

### Logout

```txt
POST /auth/logout
```

Expected response:

```json
{
  "message": "Logout successful"
}
```

After logout, the authentication cookie is cleared. Protected routes should return `401 Unauthorized` again.

