## 13. Security Test Cases

### Invalid Email

```json
{
  "email": "invalid-email",
  "username": "testuser",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123"
}
```

Expected result:

```txt
400 Bad Request
```

---

### Weak Password

```json
{
  "email": "weak@example.com",
  "username": "weakuser",
  "password": "123"
}
```

Expected result:

```txt
400 Bad Request
```

---

### SQL Injection-looking Email

```json
{
  "email": "' OR 1=1 --",
  "username": "sqltest",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123"
}
```

Expected result:

```txt
400 Bad Request
```

The email field must follow a valid email format, so this payload should be rejected.

---

### SQL Injection-looking Username

```json
{
  "email": "user5@example.com",
  "username": "' OR 1=1 --",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123"
}
```

If the username schema only checks length, this value may be stored as plain text. This does not mean SQL injection was successful. It means the username validation is too permissive.

Recommended improvement:

```ts
username: Joi.string()
  .min(3)
  .max(30)
  .pattern(/^[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+$/)
  .required()
```

After this improvement, SQL injection-looking and XSS-looking usernames should be rejected.

---

### Login Bypass Test

Test login with a SQL injection-looking email:

```json
{
  "email": "' OR 1=1 --",
  "password": "anything"
}
```

Expected result:

```txt
400 Bad Request
```

or:

```txt
401 Unauthorized
```

The application should not log in successfully.

---

### Mass Assignment Test

Try sending an unexpected `role` field during user creation:

```json
{
  "email": "normal@example.com",
  "username": "normaluser",
  "password": "StrongPassword!123",
  "role": "admin"
}
```

Expected behavior:

```txt
The client should not be able to create an admin user by sending role in the request body.
```

The backend should either reject unknown fields or ignore them.

---

### Protected Route Test

Call the protected route without login:

```txt
GET /users
```

Expected result:

```txt
401 Unauthorized
```

After login, the same request should return the user list.

